    ></script>
</div>

        <div class="more-btn-container">
            <div class="more-btn-label">More</div>


            
            <div class="social-btn">
            <a class="email-btn"
                onclick="$.event.trigger('social:share', [{type:'email', action:'share', el:this}])"
                href="mailto:?subject=The%20Illusion%20That%20Makes%20It%20Sound%20Like%20a%20Pitch%20Is%20Constantly%20Rising%20&amp;body=Discovered%20by%20the%20same%20people%20who%20brought%20you%20the%20modern%20computer%0A%0ARead%20More%3A%0Ahttp%3A%2F%2Fwww.theatlantic.com%2Ftechnology%2Farchive%2F2014%2F01%2Fthe-illusion-that-makes-it-sound-like-a-pitch-is-constantly-rising%2F283417%2F">Email</a>
            </div>

            <div class="social-btn">
            <a class="print-btn"
               href="http://www.theatlantic.com/technology/print/2014/01/the-illusion-that-makes-it-sound-like-a-pitch-is-constantly-rising/283417/"
               target="_blank"
               onclick="window.open('http://www.theatlantic.com/technology/print/2014/01/the-illusion-that-makes-it-sound-like-a-pitch-is-constantly-rising/283417/', 'Print', 'width=800,height=600,location=no,scrollbars=yes,status=no,toolbar=no,resizable=yes');return false">Print</a>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
    
    <!-- Article Main Contents -->
    <div class="article-content" itemprop="articleBody">

                                    
                
        <figure><img alt="" height="637" src="http://cdn.theatlantic.com/newsroom/img/posts/2014/01/726705899_bff918d76e_o/e2dad9303.jpg" width="570"/><figcaption class="caption">Like this, but for sound (ijzerman / Flickr)</figcaption></figure><p>I just found Meara OReilys <a href="http://illusionsongs.tumblr.com">tremendous and long-running Tumblr</a> of audio illusions. At the top is one of my favorite aural phenomena: The shepherd scale.</p>

<p>You can listen to an example here:</p>

<figure><iframe allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0" height="428" src="//www.youtube.com/embed/DfJa3IC1txI" width="570"></iframe></figure><!--INSERT IN_ARTICLE AD--><p>The Shepherd scale gives the sensation of a continuously rising or falling pitch. In the example above, the pitch seems to fall. Its the aural equivalent of the Penrose stairs (which you might recognize from an Escher drawning).</p>

<p>It sounds like that, at least. In fact, the rising tone is just the cycling between a limited set of tones, each separated by an octave.<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roger_Shepard">Roger Shepherd</a> discovered the Shepherd tone in 1967 at Bell Labs, the same New Jersey laboratory that gave humanity the transistor, the laser and multiple major operating systems and programming languages.</p>

<p>Its one more example, if a superficial one, of the deep connections between technology and culture. The shepherd scalea fluke of human cognitionwas bequeathed by the same facility that gave us many components of modern computing.</p>

<p>The tone series can be deployed effectively as a storytelling illusion. In<em>The Dark Knight </em>and the<em>Dark Knight Returns,</em>sound designers used the Shepherd scale to help the idea of the Batmobile come to life. As <a href="http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0455185/">Richard King</a>, the filmss sound designer, <a href="http://articles.latimes.com/2009/feb/04/news/en-lightsknight4">told the <em>Los Angeles Times</em></a>:</p>

<blockquote>
<p><span>The basic idea is to slightly overlap a sound with a distinct pitch (a large A/C electric motor, in this case) in different octaves. When played on a keyboard, it gives the illusion of greater and greater speed; the pod appears unstoppable.</span></p>
</blockquote>

<p>But the scale isnt merely a gimmick: Musicians can use it in surprisingly effective ways. In<em>Bar Xizam, </em>a 2007 choral work by the composerAbbie Betinis, a hummed Shepherd tone wafts up behind the words of the Persian poet<span>Hfez. I saw <em>Bar Xizam</em> performed in a massive stone church in downtown Chicago, on a snowy night three years ago. On an audience that didnt know what to expect, the effect more than mesmerizesit seems holy.</span></p>

<figure><iframe allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0" height="321" src="//www.youtube.com/embed/H0n1c_Ku2ls" width="570"></iframe></figure>
        
            </div>

</article>

